            <ObservedData>
              <Attribute Type="Description">In a 9.5-year-old boy (patient 1) with neurodevelopmental disorder with autistic features and structural brain abnormalities (NEDASB; 618859), Mattioli et al. (2020) identified a de novo heterozygous 1-bp deletion (c.782del, NM_002516.3) in exon 4 of the NOVA2 gene, predicted to result in a frameshift and premature termination (Val261GlyfsTer135). The mutation, which was found by exome sequencing and confirmed by Sanger sequencing, was not present in public databases, including gnomAD. The mutation was predicted to remove the third KH domain of the protein, which binds certain RNA loops. Since the mutation occurs in the last exon, it likely escapes nonsense-mediated mRNA decay, but NOVA2 is not expressed in blood cells, precluding confirmation. Expression of the mutation in HeLa cells showed that the truncated protein was expressed normally and localized normally to the nucleus. The authors postulated that the mutation results in a partial loss-of-function rather than a dominant-negative effect.</Attribute>
